7 Un’aura dolce, sanza mutamento 8 avere in sé, mi feria per la fronte 9 non di più colpo che soave vento;
10 per cui le fronde, tremolando, pronte 11 tutte quante piegavano a la parte 12 u’ la prim’ ombra gitta il santo monte;
13 non però dal loro esser dritto sparte 14 tanto, che li augelletti per le cime 15 lasciasser d’operare ogne lor arte;
16 ma con piena letizia l’ore prime, 17 cantando, ricevieno intra le foglie, 18 che tenevan bordone a le sue rime,
19 tal qual di ramo in ramo si raccoglie 20 per la pineta in su ’l lito di Chiassi, 21 quand’ Ëolo scilocco fuor discioglie.

query.result:
7 A sweet breeze, without change 8 having in itself, it struck me on the forehead 9 not more blow than gentle wind;
10 for which the leaves, trembling, ready 11 all completely bent to the side 12 where the first shadow throws the holy mountain;
13 not however from their being straight split 14 so, that the little birds through the peaks 15 would let them work every their art;
16 but with full joy the early hours, 17 singing, they received within the leaves, 18 that held a refrain to its rhymes,
19 just as from branch to branch it gathers 20 through the pinewood up the shore of Chiassi, 21 when Aeolus scilocco was unbound.

